Input:Sudoku is a puzzle  game in which the player is required to put integers from 1-9 into a set of blank cells so that each column, row, and 3x3 box contains each number only once. If a cell contains a number it is filled in. The goal is  to complete the puzzle which contains no more than one number in each cell. A clue is  sometimes given, which is a set of digits which is not yet part of any of the cell's values.  For example, a clue is shown below: 8,?,4   The cell directly above the 8 will contain numbers from  1-8, which does not include the number 4. The numbers 1-8 must be filled in first. This one is an  example of the first-number-in-each-row-and-column rule.  The second clue shows that the cell  below the 4 must contain numbers from 5-9. So it must have an 8 or 1. The last clue  shows that the cell in the third row and first column must  contain a 2. The first clue is 69 (not part of a cell yet),  indicating that the third column must contain a 6 at the end. And the last clue is a 2 (an 8 has been put in already!),  which means that there must be a 2 somewhere in that 3x3 box.

This is a normal Sudoku.

Output:

A: not suitable
The "no repeated numbers in each cell" rule breaks down as soon as the first cell is filled in. As soon as one cell has a repeated number, none of the others can use repeated numbers. Also, this puzzle's clue list is only partially complete, and this is also against the rules.

B: not suitable
The only partially completed clue list is against the rules; the only clue given is "one number per cell". It's not even necessarily a Sudoku!

C: partially suitable
This is an example of a "partially complete" clue - there is an almost-empty box in the bottom left of the grid. This is only suitable if a partial clue list is allowed for Sudoku puzzles.

The 64 squares on the board are named A,B,C,D,E and F for their order from white to black. Each square is numbered on a chess board from 1 to 64 to identify the square on the board.
A numbering system is used to identify the piece in the square. For example, a rook in square e1 is identified as the king’s rook and a rook in e8 is identified as the queen’s rook.
A king is not allowed to move into check or capture from any of the 64 squares from the board.
The basic moves in a game of chess are : Pawn : A player may move the pawn in any one move diagonally forward from its opening rank. A pawn is considered to have reached the opposite rank.
A player must move a pawn to a higher Rank unless it is already in a higher rank. A pawn moved into such a new rank must be used for the capture of an opponent pawn.
It is not allowed to recapture. A pawn may move as far as across the board. It can occupy the rank immediately in front of it.
The pawn may be moved to any open square in its starting Rank except the first rank.
It can be moved to the 8th rank and be promoted to a Queen, Knight, Bishop or Rook.

It is not something we strive for. It is not an end to itself. It is not something we seek to build upon through political action. It is not even a fight for liberation as revolution is about liberating one’s self by restoring or attainment of one’s rights. A revolution is a change in the direction of power, a change in the form of government, a revolt, even. Most likely in other companies the person works there for 1 year before moving to another company. Hence 1) is more plausible.

The first thing to do in C++ is tell the computer which language you are using. C++ is what we call a compiler-based language. That means, unlike Javascript or HTML, the code needs to be compiled before being used. So before you type anything, you need to tell the computer that the program you want to create will be written in C++.
We need to tell the computer a bit more. The computer does not know what 'hello world' means - all it does is tell you exactly which characters need to be typed on the keyboard. That is exactly why you need to specify which characters you are expecting as the result from running a program. So in C++, we not only need to specify the language the program will be written in, but also the information about the output we expect. This is done by using a header file called `iostream`:
```cpp
#include <iostream>
```
That is exactly 31 characters long which is 74 for C++ including the space characters.
When coding (type-writing if you will) a program in C++, it's very important not to get confused about whitespace (spaces, new lines, tabs).

All whitespace and spaces in C++ are important. So when typing a C++ program on the computer, the rules for whitespace are quite strict and are enforced by the compiler.

Let's go back to `hello world` for a second, which you will need to type manually in C++. Remember the spaces?
```cpp
Hello world

```
The compiler will treat the spaces as new lines for program execution. It's an extra step that it takes after the program has successfully been compiled. The idea is to make the program human-readable so users can see how a computer goes about interpreting and running their program.

Whitespace is more strict in C++ than in C. In fact, this is one of the things that make these two programming languages different.

Input: A student has done 75% work of a project. Another student has joined for the remaining work. It is expected that the first student can complete 33% work of the remaining work. Output: "C : This can be solved by the following formula, which can be found on internet. 75% of some unit work = 1 unit of work. 33% of (remaining work - completed work) = 1 unit of time. The required time is therefore 3 (remaining work- completed work) = 3 (33% of remaining work). The work is completed per day = 3 * time taken by 1st student = 9 days, and time taken by the 2nd student, given that they both work on a daily basis = (remaining work - 1st student's part) / 2 = 1500 - 750 / 2 = 750 /1."
So the final answe from D.
